What I Hope You Do:
Break it. Find the edge cases. Discover where it fails. Document the failures.
Improve it. Add systems. Optimize algorithms. Create better validation. Share your work.
Build with it. Create worlds. Write tools. Make games. Teach with it. Experiment wildly.
Keep it free. If you build something commercial, consider how you can give back—whether through open-source tools, free tiers, or educational access.
Collaborate. This is bigger than any one person. Share knowledge. Build together.


Acknowledgments:
This architecture stands on the shoulders of interactive fiction pioneers (Emily Short, Inkle, Choice of Games),
decades of game-design wisdom (from Zork’s hidden world modeling to Dwarf Fortress’s emergent simulation), tabletop RPG state management,
and modern AI capabilities. Structure doesn’t constrain creativity; it enables it.


